Residents of Hagar Buur village in Dadaab subcounty are living in fear following a lion invasion caused by the drought.The lions have been roaming villages in search of food after being forced out of their natural habitat kilometres away.In a week, the lions have killed five cows and a camel. Residents, led by Dertu MCA Abdi Ali, called on KWS to intervene.Ali said residents have been forced to flee their homes.When the press visited the village, 50km from Garissa town on Thursday, it was deserted.&ldquo;These lions are causing havoc. It has been a week now since they started killing our livestock, but we haven&rsquo;t heard anything from the authorities,&rdquo; Ali said.He added, &ldquo;Are they waiting for people to die before they intervene? They need to act now before it is too late.&rdquo;KWS wardens were unavailable for comment. Human-wildlife conflict has been increasing in four months. The worst-affected areas areHolugho and Ijara subcounties.The water crisis has threatened the livelihoods of residents.Two weeks ago, Garissa Senator Yusuf Haji said, &ldquo;This is the worst drought we have seen in decades.&rdquo;He added, &ldquo;I appeal to the county government and other aid agencies to intervene.&rdquo;